        // Then $a_{n-1}$ can be median of $C_1$ (size $2(n-1)+1 = 2n-1$).
        // $a_n$ can be median of $C_2$ (size $2(0)+1 = 1$).
        //
        // Let's construct the classes for $M_1 = a_{n-1}$ and $M_2 = a_n$.
        // We need to pick $k_1$ elements smaller than $a_{n-1}$ for $C_1$. We can pick $a_0, \dots, a_{k_1-1}$.
        // We need to pick $k_1$ elements larger than $a_{n-1}$ for $C_1$.
        // We need to pick $k_2$ elements smaller than $a_n$ for $C_2$.
        // We need to pick $k_2$ elements larger than $a_n$ for $C_2$.
        //
        // Let's try to make $k_1 = 0$ and $k_2 = n-1$.
        // $C_1$ has size $2(0)+1 = 1$. Its median is $a_{n-1}$. So $C_1 = \{a_{n-1}\}$.
        // $C_2$ has size $2(n-1)+1 = 2n-1$. Its median is $a_n$.
        // For $C_2$, we need $n-1$ elements smaller than $a_n$ and $n-1$ elements larger than $a_n$.
        // We have $a_0, \dots, a_{n-2}$ (total $n-1$ elements) available to be smaller than $a_n$.
        // We have $a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ (total $n-1$ elements) available to be larger than $a_n$.
        // So we can form $C_2 = \{a_0, \dots, a_{n-2}, a_n, a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}\}$.
        // This is a valid partition. $C_1 = \{a_{n-1}\}$ and $C_2 = \{a_0, \dots, a_{n-2}, a_n, a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}\}$.
        // The medians are $a_{n-1}$ and $a_n$. The difference is $|a_n - a_{n-1}|$.
        //
        // This construction always works.
        // The minimum possible absolute difference is indeed $a_n - a_{n-1}$.

        long long result = a[n] - a[n - 1];
        std::cout << result << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}

#include <iostream>
