    // If (val0_j, val1_j) = (0,1): A_j = (1^0)|(0&1) = 1|0 = 1. (val1_j = 1)
    // If (val0_j, val1_j) = (1,0): A_j = (0^1)|(1&0) = 1|0 = 1. (val1_j = 0, but A_j=1. This is wrong.)
    // If (val0_j, val1_j) = (1,1): A_j = (1^1)|(1&1) = 0|1 = 1. (val1_j = 1)
    //
    // The issue is when (val0_j, val1_j) = (1,0).
    // Here B_j must be 0. So C_j = 0 ^ 1 = 1.
    // (A_j | 0) ^ (0 ^ 1) = 0
    // A_j ^ 1 = 0
    // A_j = 1.
    // So A_j = 1, B_j = 0, C_j = 1.
    //
    // Let's try to construct A, B, C directly from the four cases for (val0_j, val1_j):
    //
    // Case (val0_j, val1_j) = (0,0): Output is always 0.
    //   ((x_j & A_j) | B_j) ^ C_j = 0
    //   If A_j=0, B_j=0, C_j=0: ((x_j & 0) | 0) ^ 0 = 0. Works.
    //
    // Case (val0_j, val1_j) = (0,1): Output is x_j.
    //   ((x_j & A_j) | B_j) ^ C_j = x_j
    //   If A_j=1, B_j=0, C_j=0: ((x_j & 1) | 0) ^ 0 = x_j. Works.
