    long long total_pairs = (long long)n * (n + 1) / 2;
    long long bad_pairs = 0;

    // max_r_for_l[i] stores the maximum r such that the substring s[i...r]
    // does NOT contain any triple pattern.
    // Initialize with n-1, meaning s[i...n-1] is initially considered bad.
    // We will update this to the smallest possible r that makes s[i...r] bad.
    // Or, more precisely, max_r_for_l[i] will store the largest index j
    // such that s[i...j] does NOT contain any triple pattern.
    // If s[i...j] does not contain a triple, then s[i...k] for k < j also does not.
    // So we are looking for the smallest j such that s[i...j] contains a triple.
    // Let's define max_valid_r[i] as the maximum r such that s[i...r] contains NO triple.
    // Initially, for any l, the substring s[l...n-1] might contain a triple.
    // We want to find the smallest r_min[l] such that s[l...r_min[l]] contains a triple.
    // Then all pairs (l, r) with r >= r_min[l] are good.
    // All pairs (l, r) with r < r_min[l] are bad.
    // The number of bad pairs for a given l is r_min[l] - l.
    // If no triple exists starting at l, then r_min[l] = n.
    // So, bad_pairs = sum_{l=0}^{n-1} (r_min[l] - l).

